#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:6
msgid "Skip and xfail: dealing with tests that can not succeed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:8
msgid ""
"If you have test functions that cannot be run on certain platforms or that "
"you expect to fail you can mark them accordingly or you may call helper "
"functions during execution of setup or test functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:12
msgid ""
"A *skip* means that you expect your test to pass unless the environment (e."
"g. wrong Python interpreter, missing dependency) prevents it to run. And "
"*xfail* means that your test can run but you expect it to fail because there "
"is an implementation problem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:17
msgid ""
"``pytest`` counts and lists *skip* and *xfail* tests separately. Detailed "
"information about skipped/xfailed tests is not shown by default to avoid "
"cluttering the output.  You can use the ``-r`` option to see details "
"corresponding to the \"short\" letters shown in the test progress::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:22
msgid "py.test -rxs  # show extra info on skips and xfails"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:24
msgid "(See :ref:`how to change command line options defaults`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:30
msgid "Marking a test function to be skipped"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:34
msgid ""
"The simplest way to skip a test function is to mark it with the ``skip`` "
"decorator which may be passed an optional ``reason``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:37
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skip(reason=\"no way of currently testing this\")\n"
"def test_the_unknown():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:44
msgid "``skipif``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:46
msgid "2.4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:48
msgid ""
"If you wish to skip something conditionally then you can use ``skipif`` "
"instead. Here is an example of marking a test function to be skipped when "
"run on a Python3.3 interpreter::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:52
msgid ""
"import sys\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.version_info < (3,3),\n"
"                    reason=\"requires python3.3\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:58
msgid ""
"During test function setup the condition (\"sys.version_info >= (3,3)\") is "
"checked.  If it evaluates to True, the test function will be skipped with "
"the specified reason.  Note that pytest enforces specifying a reason in "
"order to report meaningful \"skip reasons\" (e.g. when using ``-rs``). If "
"the condition is a string, it will be evaluated as python expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:64
msgid ""
"You can share skipif markers between modules.  Consider this test module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:66
msgid ""
"# content of test_mymodule.py\n"
"\n"
"import mymodule\n"
"minversion = pytest.mark.skipif(mymodule.__versioninfo__ < (1,1),\n"
"                                reason=\"at least mymodule-1.1 required\")\n"
"@minversion\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:75
msgid "You can import it from another test module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:77
msgid ""
"# test_myothermodule.py\n"
"from test_mymodule import minversion\n"
"\n"
"@minversion\n"
"def test_anotherfunction():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:84
msgid ""
"For larger test suites it's usually a good idea to have one file where you "
"define the markers which you then consistently apply throughout your test "
"suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:88
msgid ""
"Alternatively, the pre pytest-2.4 way to specify :ref:`condition strings "
"<string conditions>` instead of booleans will remain fully supported in "
"future versions of pytest.  It couldn't be easily used for importing markers "
"between test modules so it's no longer advertised as the primary method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:95
msgid "Skip all test functions of a class or module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:97
msgid ""
"You can use the ``skipif`` decorator (and any other marker) on classes::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:99
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform == 'win32',\n"
"                    reason=\"does not run on windows\")\n"
"class TestPosixCalls:\n"
"\n"
"    def test_function(self):\n"
"        \"will not be setup or run under 'win32' platform\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:106
msgid ""
"If the condition is true, this marker will produce a skip result for each of "
"the test methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:109
msgid ""
"If you want to skip all test functions of a module, you must use the "
"``pytestmark`` name on the global level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:112
msgid ""
"# test_module.py\n"
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.skipif(...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:117
msgid ""
"If multiple \"skipif\" decorators are applied to a test function, it will be "
"skipped if any of the skip conditions is true."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:125
msgid "Mark a test function as expected to fail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:127
msgid ""
"You can use the ``xfail`` marker to indicate that you expect a test to fail::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:130
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:134
msgid ""
"This test will be run but no traceback will be reported when it fails. "
"Instead terminal reporting will list it in the \"expected to "
"fail\" (``XFAIL``) or \"unexpectedly passing\" (``XPASS``) sections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:139
msgid "``strict`` parameter"
msgstr "``strict`` 參數"

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:143
msgid ""
"Both ``XFAIL`` and ``XPASS`` don't fail the test suite, unless the "
"``strict`` keyword-only parameter is passed as ``True``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:146
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(strict=True)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:153
msgid ""
"This will make ``XPASS`` (\"unexpectedly passing\") results from this test "
"to fail the test suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:155
msgid ""
"You can change the default value of the ``strict`` parameter using the "
"``xfail_strict`` ini option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:158
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"xfail_strict=true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:165
msgid "``reason`` parameter"
msgstr "``reason`` 參數"

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:167
msgid ""
"As with skipif_ you can also mark your expectation of a failure on a "
"particular platform::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:170
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(sys.version_info >= (3,3),\n"
"                   reason=\"python3.3 api changes\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:177
msgid "``raises`` parameter"
msgstr "``raises`` 參數"

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:179
msgid ""
"If you want to be more specific as to why the test is failing, you can "
"specify a single exception, or a list of exceptions, in the ``raises`` "
"argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:182
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(raises=RuntimeError)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:188
msgid ""
"Then the test will be reported as a regular failure if it fails with an "
"exception not mentioned in ``raises``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:192
msgid "``run`` parameter"
msgstr "``run`` 參數"

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:194
msgid ""
"If a test should be marked as xfail and reported as such but should not be "
"even executed, use the ``run`` parameter as ``False``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:197
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(run=False)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:203
msgid ""
"This is specially useful for marking crashing tests for later inspection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:207
msgid "Ignoring xfail marks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:209
msgid "By specifying on the commandline::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:211
msgid "pytest --runxfail"
msgstr "pytest --runxfail"

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:213
msgid ""
"you can force the running and reporting of an ``xfail`` marked test as if it "
"weren't marked at all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:217
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:219
msgid "Here is a simple test file with the several usages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:221
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"xfail = pytest.mark.xfail\n"
"\n"
"@xfail\n"
"def test_hello():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(run=False)\n"
"def test_hello2():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(\"hasattr(os, 'sep')\")\n"
"def test_hello3():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(reason=\"bug 110\")\n"
"def test_hello4():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"@xfail('pytest.__version__[0] != \"17\"')\n"
"def test_hello5():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"def test_hello6():\n"
"    pytest.xfail(\"reason\")\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(raises=IndexError)\n"
"def test_hello7():\n"
"    x = []\n"
"    x[1] = 1\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:223
msgid "Running it with the report-on-xfail option gives this output::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:225
msgid ""
"example $ py.test -rx xfail_demo.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/example, inifile:\n"
"collected 7 items\n"
"\n"
"xfail_demo.py xxxxxxx\n"
"======= short test summary info ========\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello2\n"
"  reason: [NOTRUN]\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello3\n"
"  condition: hasattr(os, 'sep')\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello4\n"
"  bug 110\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello5\n"
"  condition: pytest.__version__[0] != \"17\"\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello6\n"
"  reason: reason\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello7\n"
"\n"
"======= 7 xfailed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:249
msgid "xfail signature summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:251
msgid ""
"Here's the signature of the ``xfail`` marker, using Python 3 keyword-only "
"arguments syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:254
msgid ""
"def xfail(condition=None, *, reason=None, raises=None, run=True, "
"strict=False):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:263
msgid "Skip/xfail with parametrize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:265
msgid ""
"It is possible to apply markers like skip and xfail to individual test "
"instances when using parametrize::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:268
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize((\"n\", \"expected\"), [\n"
"    (1, 2),\n"
"pytest.mark.xfail((1, 0)),\n"
"    pytest.mark.xfail(reason=\"some bug\")((1, 3)),\n"
"    (2, 3),\n"
"    (3, 4),\n"
"    (4, 5),\n"
"    pytest.mark.skipif(\"sys.version_info >= (3,0)\")((10, 11)),\n"
"])\n"
"def test_increment(n, expected):\n"
"    assert n + 1 == expected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:284
msgid "Imperative xfail from within a test or setup function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:286
msgid ""
"If you cannot declare xfail- of skipif conditions at import time you can "
"also imperatively produce an according outcome imperatively, in test or "
"setup code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:290
msgid ""
"def test_function():\n"
"    if not valid_config():\n"
"        pytest.xfail(\"failing configuration (but should work)\")\n"
"        # or\n"
"        pytest.skip(\"unsupported configuration\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:298
msgid "Skipping on a missing import dependency"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:300
msgid ""
"You can use the following import helper at module level or within a test or "
"test setup function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:303
msgid "docutils = pytest.importorskip(\"docutils\")"
msgstr "docutils = pytest.importorskip(\"docutils\")"

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:305
msgid ""
"If ``docutils`` cannot be imported here, this will lead to a skip outcome of "
"the test.  You can also skip based on the version number of a library::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:309
msgid "docutils = pytest.importorskip(\"docutils\", minversion=\"0.3\")"
msgstr "docutils = pytest.importorskip(\"docutils\", minversion=\"0.3\")"

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:311
msgid ""
"The version will be read from the specified module's ``__version__`` "
"attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:318
msgid "specifying conditions as strings versus booleans"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:320
msgid ""
"Prior to pytest-2.4 the only way to specify skipif/xfail conditions was to "
"use strings::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:323
msgid ""
"import sys\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(\"sys.version_info >= (3,3)\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:328
msgid ""
"During test function setup the skipif condition is evaluated by calling "
"``eval('sys.version_info >= (3,0)', namespace)``.  The namespace contains "
"all the module globals, and ``os`` and ``sys`` as a minimum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:332
msgid ""
"Since pytest-2.4 `condition booleans`_ are considered preferable because "
"markers can then be freely imported between test modules. With strings you "
"need to import not only the marker but all variables everything used by the "
"marker, which violates encapsulation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:337
msgid ""
"The reason for specifying the condition as a string was that ``pytest`` can "
"report a summary of skip conditions based purely on the condition string. "
"With conditions as booleans you are required to specify a ``reason`` string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:341
msgid ""
"Note that string conditions will remain fully supported and you are free to "
"use them if you have no need for cross-importing markers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:344
msgid ""
"The evaluation of a condition string in ``pytest.mark."
"skipif(conditionstring)`` or ``pytest.mark.xfail(conditionstring)`` takes "
"place in a namespace dictionary which is constructed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:348
msgid ""
"the namespace is initialized by putting the ``sys`` and ``os`` modules and "
"the pytest ``config`` object into it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:351
msgid ""
"updated with the module globals of the test function for which the "
"expression is applied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:354
msgid ""
"The pytest ``config`` object allows you to skip based on a test "
"configuration value which you might have added::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:357
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skipif(\"not config.getvalue('db')\")\n"
"def test_function(...):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:361
msgid "The equivalent with \"boolean conditions\" is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:363
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skipif(not pytest.config.getvalue(\"db\"),\n"
"                    reason=\"--db was not specified\")\n"
"def test_function(...):\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:370
msgid ""
"You cannot use ``pytest.config.getvalue()`` in code imported before py."
"test's argument parsing takes place.  For example, ``conftest.py`` files are "
"imported before command line parsing and thus ``config.getvalue()`` will not "
"execute correctly."
msgstr ""
